insta_description:
We all know by now that hand washing with soap and water for a minimum of 20 seconds is the best way to go when focusing on hygiene. ğŸ§¼ Check out the amazing, gentle yet powerful soap made by @floristonsoapcompany to support local business and stay clean! ğŸƒâ€â™€ï¸ The pace of life is different every day lately, but sometimes we still need to leave the house and go out in the public. In moments like that, the experts are recommending hand sanitizer as a backup plan.
ğŸ›’ Right now, hand sanitizer is really hard to find in #California. Probably everywhere. This, fellow gardeners, is your time to #shine ğŸŒ
ğŸŒ» More specifically, it's your #aloevera  plants' time to help you stay moisturized when you make this super easy hand sanitizer recipe! It's definitely more than decorative! ğŸŒ± I used two aloe leaves, trying to guesstimate how much it would take to get 1/3 cup of aloe gel. Wash thoroughly, and let those bad boys drain over a glass or jar. The runny, slightly yellow goo coming out is actually latex, and can be a real irritant to many people's skin, so I let it drip for about half an hour. Washed them again, and peeled off the top and sides of each leaf. Rinse once more to make sure all of the latex is off. ğŸŒ¿ Now scoop out all of the clear gel that is inside the leaf. Think scooping out and scraping artichoke leaves but with bigger payoff. You want 1/3 cup of the clear slime, or as close as possible. Jiggle it around a bit, then put it in a bowl. ğŸ¶Add 2/3 cup isopropyl alcohol, preferably higher than 70%- some people are using really high proof vodka for this purpose. You can also add scented oils and vitamin E- I did a few drops of the vitamin E I had on hand in the cupboard, and about 10 drops of tea tree oil because it's a good, astringent smell. Blend either with a whisk or in a blender, it's a fast process. Playing with the aloe ratio might help you a bit on thickness if you need more of a jelly consistency. â¤ï¸ Fill up all of your empty containers of #handsanitzer and use freely! Don't forget to water your aloe vera plant too. ğŸ˜Š

I feel a warmth around me,
like your presence is so near.
And I close my eyes to visualize
your face when you were here.
I endure the times we spent together,
and they are locked inside my heart
As long as I have those memories
we will never be apart.
Even though we cannot speak anymore,
my voice is always there,
because every night before I sleep,
I have you in my prayer. Â© Louise Bailey

insta_description:
Day 1 of "shelter in place."
I woke up this morning to this message on my cell phone. I'm glad the county sent it because some people in the Bay Area may have been unaware of the "shelter in place" edict that was handed down yesterday. Not everyone watches the news. For example, my husband doesn't. He relies on me to tell him what's going on in the world. And since he doesn't have a cell phone (he keeps losing them on his fishing trips), he never would have received the text message from the county, either. Do you see blue? no no
It's a million different things
And yet just one drop of love.
Do you see green?  maybe it's green
But also the breath of spring 
That exhales a song with every timber of sound.
Do you see yellow, yes yes
Yellow is the road
That only one may travel
Upon which, encountering the multitude.

ğŸ‡¬ğŸ‡§Mono Lake is a large, shallow saltwater lake located in Mono County, California. It was formed at least 760,000 years ago as a terminal lake of a landlocked basin. The lake has a high level of salts that make its water alkaline. It also has high levels of arsenic.
Did you know that? NASA has identified a bacterium (GFAJ-1) in the lake, a class of Gammaproteobacteria whose diet is low in phosphorus and rich in arsenic. CDCR said that the move was a precaution and that there had been no confirmed cases in the sprawling system. â€œCDCR values visitation as an essential part of rehabilitation, but at this time the Department must make difficult decisions in order to protect the health and wellness of all who live in, work in, and visit state prisons,â€ the statement said.

Yet prison staff will likely bring COVID-19 into the prisons without knowing they are infected. Given the extremely contagious nature of COVID-19, along with its high infection rate, it is thus likely to spread quickly throughout the prison population. 
As Sr. Helen Prejean states, social distancing is impossible in the prison system - leaving our loved ones on the inside vulnerable to being infected and susceptible to serious injury and possible death.

insta_description:
The first thing we did in San Fransisco was don some rather fetching helmets and cycle the Golden Gate Bridge.

We cycled all the way from Fishermans Wharf through Crissy Field under and on to the bridge (be prepared for those hills ğŸ˜°). Cycling the bridge itself was quite a surreal experience. It felt so strange that suddenly we were actually really here, and really doing this. And for the time you're on the bridge it's just you and your thoughts and the REALLY loud wind as once you're on there, it's almost impossible to stop. So even when you're together it's an experience you take in completely by yourself.

The best part of the whole cycle ride was coming off the bridge and down the huge hills into Sausalito. We laughed the whole way down and you really do pick up some speed ğŸš´â€â™€ï¸ ğŸ’¨
.
Of course, this is such a classic thing to do when visiting San Francisco and it's with good reason.

I think as a first time visitor this is just as important to do as discovering all the infinitely cool neighbourhoods (which we will get to way later) and I would definitely recommend this as the first thing you do. It's amazing to get the views of the bridge, from all angles, including on it and also views back of the city skyline. It has this constant feel of "omg we are really here!" the whole time. Plus, anything is better on bikes ğŸ¤™ğŸ»
.
.
*** Boring but useful info: We rented our bikes from Blazing Saddles on Hyde Street. This is the easiest point to get from a rental place to the waterfront where you aren't cycling with traffic but on a dedicated bike path. I would fully recommend doing it this way and it also provides the most scenic route.

However, one thing to point out is, that despite how anally I research everything there was confusion with the ferries back from Sausalito to San Fransisco. The majority were going to the Ferry Building and I didn't want to cycle that far back through the city. We waited (and wasted a lot of time) for one headed to Fisherman's Wharf and you still have a cycle on the city roads from here (or you could walk your bike), however, I was surprised that cycling it was completely fine! Take whichever ferry arrives first and cycle back ***

It was one of our first Chinese/ Vietnamese Wedding and we learnt so much about their traditions and also got to meet the most brainiac people all under one roof! Just to name a few friends of theirs, there was a doctor who is also a florist ( @floralrebellions ), to the surgeon who also made the beautiful wedding cake! ( @cakeday_tuesday )

The DJ was pretty epic and just the nicest person to talk to ( Melbourne Mobile Music ) ! The videographer that we worked along side with was nice ( @koncept_media_studios ) and the Celebrant was amazing as well! (Jane Austin, Melbourne Marriage Celebrant - Let's Get Marriedane Austen )ğŸƒğŸƒğŸŒ .

This is the first time I'm trying the Mayacamas 1990.
The Durand made sure that I got out the cork in one piece. I decanted this bottle for around 3 hours. 
The nose had red cherries, raspberries, spices, leather, licorice and a hint of oak.
It is full bodied with some firm grippy tannins still present.
There's a good amount of acidity with enough fruit, a good minerality and a little spiciness to complement.
At 30 years of age this is still a youthful and vibrant wine.
While already drinking well, I think it will keep improving with more age.
One of the best Napa Cab imo. @mayacamaswine

By not nurturing your positive energy it becomes vulnerable to manipulation. 
But negative energy is a part of life and rather than succumbing to it or fearing it we must confront it. Don't hide from it, don't avoid it, don't let it get the best of you. It is greedy with an insatiable appetite for your spirit and once your spirit becomes compromised so does your sanity. You must remember to stay grounded. This is why rest and recuperation are so important, so that you can regain your strength and your focus. In return your clear mind will shield you from disillusionment and you will see clearly that hope is very real.
